      "source": [
        "Against intuition, this actually works. This is because an assignment statement is evaluated **right to left**. First the expression on the right of the `=` is evaluated, and then the result is assigned to the variable on the left.\n",
        "\n",
        "Changing variables in this way occurs so commonly that there is built-in shorthand for it. The result of the first line could have been achieved with `x += 5`. This **syntactic sugar** is available for all the simple operations `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `**`, and `%` that we covered earlier."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "JdXMCt4Orst_",
